data.content:
Here's the complete migration:

## Pattern Inventory

| Original API | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Request termination (calls `Thread.Abort`) | Return from the action â€” no equivalent needed |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `endResponse=true` triggers `Thread.Abort` | Return `Redirect(url)` â€” an `IActionResult` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control-flow catch block | Remove entirely â€” no abort exceptions exist |

## Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core / .NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // In ASP.NET Core, return a FileResult instead of writing
        // directly to the response stream. No Response.End() needed â€”
        // returning ends the action naturally.
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAfterProcess()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Redirect(url) returns a RedirectResult â€” no Thread.Abort,
            // no endResponse parameter. The framework handles it.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) â€” it doesn't exist in .NET 8.
        // OperationCanceledException is the modern equivalent if you
        // need to handle client disconnects (see pitfalls below).
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `Response.End()` â†’ just return**
ASP.NET Core has no `Response.End()`. Returning an `IActionResult` cleanly ends the response. For file downloads, `File()` sets headers and streams the content automatically.

**2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` â†’ `return Redirect(url)`**
The `true` (endResponse) parameter existed solely to call `Thread.Abort` and prevent code after the redirect from executing. In ASP.NET Core, `return Redirect(url)` exits the action method naturally â€” no abort needed.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` â†’ removed**
This catch block only existed to swallow the exception that `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw. Since redirects no longer throw, the block is dead code. Remove it.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---|---|
| Code after `Response.Redirect` still executes | In WebForms, `endResponse=true` aborted the thread to stop execution. In ASP.NET Core, use `return Redirect(url)` so `return` stops execution â€” don't just call `HttpContext.Response.Redirect()` without returning. |
| Swapping `ThreadAbortException` for `OperationCanceledException` blindly | Only catch `OperationCanceledException` if you use `HttpContext.RequestAborted` for long-running work. Don't add it as a 1:1 replacement for the old catch block. |
| Writing to `Response.Body` after returning an `IActionResult` | In ASP.NET Core, once you return a result, the framework owns the response. Don't mix `Response.Write` calls with `IActionResult` returns. |
| Not handling `IsAuthenticated` null reference | `User.Identity` can be `null` in ASP.NET Core if no auth middleware runs. Use `User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? false`. |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` in timeout scenarios | Not applicable here, but if you add timeout logic, always wrap `CancellationTokenSource` in `using`. |

## Bonus: Handling Client Disconnects

If `GenerateReport()` is long-running and you want to stop when the client disconnects (the modern equivalent of request termination):

```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core automatically binds HttpContext.RequestAborted
    // to this parameter. If the client disconnects, the token fires.
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
    return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

This is the cooperative cancellation model replacing the old preemptive `Thread.Abort` approach â€” the code **voluntarily** checks the token rather than being forcibly killed.
